<i>negotiated settlement to the conflict
is at hand.</i>

454
00:28:32,200 --> 00:28:36,440
<i>In the meantime, the public is urged
to remain calm and to continue normally.</i>

455
00:28:36,600 --> 00:28:38,840
(BIRD CHIRPING)

456
00:28:42,600 --> 00:28:44,520
(SHOUTING, SIRENS BLARING)

457
00:28:44,680 --> 00:28:47,000
(GLASS SHATTERING)

458
00:28:47,160 --> 00:28:49,160
(ANGRY SHOUTING)

459
00:28:54,160 --> 00:28:56,080
(SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE)

460
00:28:56,240 --> 00:28:58,240
(SHOUTING IN DISTANCE)

461
00:29:08,480 --> 00:29:10,480
(DISTANT COMMOTION)

462
00:29:13,520 --> 00:29:15,520
(SHOUTING AND SIRENS IN DISTANCE)

463
00:29:19,600 --> 00:29:21,600
Are you all right, love?

464
00:29:22,560 --> 00:29:24,160
It's noisy.

465
00:29:26,800 --> 00:29:28,720
It must be t'pubs turning out.

466
00:29:28,880 --> 00:29:30,880
(CLOCK TICKING)

467
00:29:43,840 --> 00:29:46,120
RADIO:
<i>People are alarmed about what they see</i>

468
00:29:46,280 --> 00:29:49,160
<i>as a lack of advice or information
from the Government.</i>

469
00:29:49,320 --> 00:29:52,280
MINISTER: <i>The policy of the government
is quite clear on the matter.</i>

470
00:29:52,440 --> 00:29:53,920
<i>We are urging people to keep calm.</i>

471
00:29:54,080 --> 00:29:56,080
Doing a moonlight flit, then?

472
00:29:56,440 --> 00:30:00,760
No, we're going over to our Jack's in
Lincolnshire while things get sorted out.

473
00:30:00,920 --> 00:30:02,600
I reckon we should be safer over there.

474
00:30:02,760 --> 00:30:06,120
Carol, stop messing about. Come inside
the house and do something to help.

475
00:30:06,280 --> 00:30:09,200
- Yeah.
- We'll not be safe anywhere, as far as I see.

476
00:30:09,360 --> 00:30:13,960
I don't know. We've a better chance of
surviving in t'country, really, haven't we?

477
00:30:14,120 --> 00:30:17,600
I mean, where our Jack lives,
there's only a row of houses and a pub.

478
00:30:17,760 --> 00:30:19,880
I don't think they're gonna bomb that,
are they?

479
00:30:20,040 --> 00:30:22,760
- Well, I think that's about it, Ron.
CAROL: Mum!

480
00:30:23,320 --> 00:30:25,480
- Carol?
- Have you turned that gas off?

481
00:30:25,640 --> 00:30:28,336
I hope so. We don't want the whole street
blowing up while you're away.

482
00:30:28,360 --> 00:30:30,880
- Come on, Carol.
- Spot! I'm coming.

483
00:30:32,080 --> 00:30:33,680
I can't find our Spot.

484
00:30:33,840 --> 00:30:37,000
He was here a minute ago, wasn't he?
Have you looked inside the house?

485
00:30:37,160 --> 00:30:40,400
I've looked upstairs, along t'street,
next door neighbour's garden.

486
00:30:40,560 --> 00:30:43,160
It's ridiculous, all this. Spot?
(WHISTLES)

487
00:30:44,160 --> 00:30:45,160
Spot?

488
00:30:45,320 --> 00:30:46,840
MRS STOTHARD:
He was here a minute ago.

489
00:30:46,920 --> 00:30:48,840
- Come on.
- He'll be here in a minute.

490
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:50,360
I know he will be!

491
00:30:50,520 --> 00:30:52,440
Spot! Come on!

492
00:30:52,600 --> 00:30:54,520
MR STOTHARD: Come on, love.
- Where is he?

493
00:30:54,680 --> 00:30:57,600
- Come on, love. We're going without him.
- I've looked upstairs.

494
00:30:57,760 --> 00:30:59,760
- Oh, Mum, tell him. Mum!
- Honestly!

495
00:30:59,920 --> 00:31:01,840
- Spot!
- You're being a right fool.

496
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:05,000
- Nothing'll happen.
- We're not standing about here all day,

497
00:31:05,160 --> 00:31:06,920
waiting for a bloody dog, get in!

498
00:31:07,080 --> 00:31:08,680
Don't be so cruel. We can't leave him.

499
00:31:08,840 --> 00:31:10,520
- Spot!
- Carol, get in.

500
00:31:10,680 --> 00:31:12,600
- Get in!
CAROL: Spot!

501
00:31:12,760 --> 00:31:14,640
Spot! Come on, Spot!

502
00:31:14,800 --> 00:31:17,200
<i>- We've had a newsflash from Bonn.</i>
- Get in you bloody thing!

503
00:31:17,320 --> 00:31:20,760
<i>The Russians have cut the road links
into and out of West Berlin.</i>

504
00:31:20,920 --> 00:31:22,520
See you, then, Bill.

505
00:31:22,680 --> 00:31:25,160
<i>- Air communications have been severed.</i>
- Let's hope so.

506
00:31:25,320 --> 00:31:28,560
<i>Details are still coming in but
it seems an American Army convoy</i>

507
00:31:28,720 --> 00:31:32,920
<i>bound for West Berlin has been turned back
at Helmstedt on the East German border.</i>

508
00:31:33,080 --> 00:31:36,920
<i>Unconfirmed reports say the Russians have
offered a safe passage out of the city</i>

509
00:31:37,080 --> 00:31:39,280
<i>to the US, British and French garrisons.</i>

510
00:31:39,440 --> 00:31:43,320
<i>It's not clear if this move is connected
with yesterday's riots in East Germany.</i>

511
00:31:43,480 --> 00:31:47,080
<i>We'll bring you more details on the story
as soon as we have them.</i>

512
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:57,000
(INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

513
00:32:00,200 --> 00:32:02,200
(PHONE BUZZES)

514
00:32:03,120 --> 00:32:05,120
Sutton here.

515
00:32:12,160 --> 00:32:14,600
Yes, I understand.
Do I have to go right away?

516
00:32:14,760 --> 00:32:16,760
No? When?

517
00:32:17,960 --> 00:32:19,760
Yes, I see.

518
00:32:25,240 --> 00:32:29,320
<i>Local authorities have been given the power
to suspend certain peacetime functions</i>

519
00:32:29,480 --> 00:32:33,120
<i>and to requisition premises
and materials for civil defence purposes.</i>

520
00:32:33,280 --> 00:32:36,960
<i>A Government spokesman said
that this was a precautionary move only,</i>

521
00:32:37,120 --> 00:32:39,120
<i>it was not a cause for alarm.</i>

522
00:33:08,600 --> 00:33:10,920
- (CAR DOOR CLOSES)
MAN: All right, love.

523
00:33:13,240 --> 00:33:15,240
Take your time.

524
00:33:15,680 --> 00:33:18,280
<i>The AA and RAC have reported
heavy congestion</i>

525
00:33:18,440 --> 00:33:20,240
<i>on roads up and down the country,</i>

526
00:33:20,400 --> 00:33:23,640
<i>particularly those leading to Wales
and the West Country.</i>

527
00:33:23,800 --> 00:33:27,760
<i>The police are urging motorists
not to travel unless absolutely necessary</i>

528
00:33:27,920 --> 00:33:30,480
<i>and, if it is essential,
to use only minor roads</i>

529
00:33:30,640 --> 00:33:34,520
<i>and leave motorways and intercity
trunk routes clear for official traffic.</i>

530
00:33:34,680 --> 00:33:37,240
<i>A full list
of designated essential service routes</i>

531
00:33:37,400 --> 00:33:40,240
<i>is posted outside
your local authority headquarters.</i>

532
00:33:40,400 --> 00:33:44,920
<i>It includes the M1, M18, A63 and A629.</i>

533
00:34:08,560 --> 00:34:10,560
(HELICOPTER WHIRRING)

534
00:34:11,800 --> 00:34:14,560
MAN (OVER PA SYSTEM):
<i>This is an essential service route.</i>

535
00:34:14,720 --> 00:34:16,640
<i>This is an essential service route.</i>

536
00:34:18,640 --> 00:34:19,736
<i>Unless you have official
or essential business...</i>

537
00:34:19,760 --> 00:34:22,080
We're trying to get across to relatives
in Lincolnshire.

538
00:34:22,240 --> 00:34:24,840
Not this way, you're not.
Essential services only, this road.

539
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:27,840
- You'll have to find another route.
- That's bloody ridiculous!

540
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:29,920
You can't just stop people like that.

541
00:34:30,080 --> 00:34:33,920
Excuse me. Where are you going?
Sorry, love, you can't go there...

542
00:34:34,080 --> 00:34:36,240
- You just can't stop people...
- I tell you what.

543
00:34:36,400 --> 00:34:38,040
Try Junction 35/36 of the M1.

544
00:34:38,200 --> 00:34:41,000
They've opened up the hard shoulder
for single-line traffic only.

545
00:34:41,160 --> 00:34:43,320
Imagine what it'll be like,
it'll be chock-a-block.

546
00:34:43,480 --> 00:34:47,040
If I were you, I'd go home and sit tight.
That's what they're advising people to do.

547
00:34:47,200 --> 00:34:51,200
PA: <i>Please find an alternative route.
This route is for essential traffic only.</i>

548
00:34:54,640 --> 00:34:58,880
<i>There's growing evidence overnight from
scientists and observers in many countries</i>

549
00:34:59,040 --> 00:35:01,800
<i>that there have been two nuclear explosions
in the Middle East.</i>

550
00:35:01,960 --> 00:35:06,040
<i>There's no official confirmation of what
has happened and the Foreign Office...</i>

551
00:35:06,200 --> 00:35:08,000
I've put half a dozen in.

552
00:35:08,160 --> 00:35:10,080
I can fetch some more if you like.

553
00:35:10,240 --> 00:35:12,240
No, that'll be plenty.

554
00:35:13,040 --> 00:35:14,720
Well, tell him to improvise, then.

555
00:35:15,520 --> 00:35:17,120
Right.

556
00:35:19,920 --> 00:35:22,360
Clive, you don't think anything's
really going to happen?

557
00:35:22,520 --> 00:35:24,840
No, it's just a precaution, that's all.

558
00:35:26,480 --> 00:35:28,480
Have you had a shave this morning?

559
00:35:29,320 --> 00:35:32,640
Oh, you should never have said you'd do it.
You don't have to.

560
00:35:32,800 --> 00:35:34,720
You won't get the sack if you refuse.

561
00:35:34,880 --> 00:35:36,800
Look, Marjorie,

562
00:35:36,960 --> 00:35:39,160
it's difficult for me as well, you know.

563
00:35:40,120 --> 00:35:42,760
I don't want to go
and leave you and the children.

564
00:35:42,920 --> 00:35:44,920
Well, then, why are you going?

565
00:35:45,840 --> 00:35:48,800
- Somebody's got to pick up the pieces if...
- (PHONE BUZZES)

566
00:35:49,560 --> 00:35:52,640
Why didn't you say something before
if you were worried about it?

567
00:35:52,800 --> 00:35:55,480
You never said anything
when I went away on those courses.

568
00:35:56,800 --> 00:35:57,920
Sutton here.

569
00:35:58,080 --> 00:36:02,000
<i>- Unconfirmed reports from Islamabad...</i>
- Yes, in half an hour's time.

570
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:06,120
I should be getting off now, if I were you.
The roads will be getting busy.

571
00:36:06,280 --> 00:36:08,160
Well, use your common sense, man.

572
00:36:08,320 --> 00:36:10,320
How should I know?

573
00:36:11,640 --> 00:36:13,560
Marjorie, leave that.

574
00:36:13,720 --> 00:36:17,120
- I'll ring you later.
<i>- ...near the country's border with Iran.</i>

575
00:36:17,280 --> 00:36:20,000
- What?
<i>- The evacuation of the area is reported.</i>

576
00:36:21,680 --> 00:36:22,760
Yes.

577
00:36:24,240 --> 00:36:25,560
Yes.

578
00:36:26,280 --> 00:36:30,000
SPEAKER: It is imperative,
while there is still time left,

579
00:36:31,080 --> 00:36:33,480
that the TUC call a general strike

580
00:36:33,640 --> 00:36:37,640
in protest against this disaster
which faces us all.

581
00:36:37,800 --> 00:36:39,720
(CHEERING)

582
00:36:39,880 --> 00:36:41,800
(JEERING, ANGRY SHOUTING)

583
00:36:41,960 --> 00:36:43,880
That's what'll destroy this country!

584
00:36:44,040 --> 00:36:46,640
There is still time to avert disaster,

585
00:36:47,480 --> 00:36:52,520
if we act resolutely and show
both the Russians and the Americans

586
00:36:53,360 --> 00:36:57,320
that we will have no truck
with their warmongering!

587
00:36:57,480 --> 00:36:59,400
What about the Falklands?

588
00:36:59,560 --> 00:37:03,200
What about the Falklands? Listen, mate,
there's nobody more patriotic than I am.

589
00:37:03,360 --> 00:37:05,976
I've been trying to get us out of
the Common Market for bloody years!

590
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:07,520
(CHEERING)

591
00:37:07,680 --> 00:37:09,560
But first...

592
00:37:09,720 --> 00:37:11,720
(CLAMOURING)

593
00:37:15,760 --> 00:37:18,320
Please do not play into their hands!

594
00:37:18,480 --> 00:37:20,480
This is a peaceful demonstration!

595
00:37:21,800 --> 00:37:24,960
We are exercising our right of free speech!

596
00:37:26,280 --> 00:37:30,200
The police have no right
to stop this demonstration!

597
00:37:30,360 --> 00:37:32,360
Do not play into their hands!

598
00:37:33,240 --> 00:37:35,120
You have no right...

599
00:37:35,280 --> 00:37:37,280
(CLAMOURING)

600
00:37:41,800 --> 00:37:43,080
Tin openers!

601
00:37:43,240 --> 00:37:45,880
£1.50 a go. Come on, all of you!

602
00:37:46,040 --> 00:37:48,760
£1.50 could save your life!

603
00:37:50,600 --> 00:37:52,600
(DISTANT COMMOTION)

604
00:38:08,040 --> 00:38:10,040
(SHOUTING AND CLAMOURING)

605
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:22,520
- Morning, Clive.
- Morning, Alan.

606
00:38:22,680 --> 00:38:25,360
- What's it like in there?
- It's a bit primitive. Take a look.

607
00:38:25,520 --> 00:38:27,520
We'll get it organised.

608
00:38:28,120 --> 00:38:30,560
Where the hell is everybody?
Only half of them are here.

609
00:38:30,720 --> 00:38:33,680
- You know Steve, the Information Officer?
- Where the hell is everybody?

610
00:38:33,840 --> 00:38:37,480
- Jeff rang in, says his car's broken down.
- That's no good, is it? How many missing?

611
00:38:37,640 --> 00:38:39,120
- About ten.
- Get on the phone.

612
00:38:39,280 --> 00:38:41,760
Tell 'em I want 'em here immediately.
Which is my desk?

613
00:38:41,920 --> 00:38:43,640
Straight through.

614
00:38:43,800 --> 00:38:45,360
Mind your head.

615
00:38:45,520 --> 00:38:47,840
Don't see any sign
of the Emergency Committee, do you?

616
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:50,440
You know what those bloody councillors
are like.

617
00:38:50,600 --> 00:38:54,520
- They're not getting paid for this, are they?
- This is it, the best I could do.

618
00:38:54,680 --> 00:38:57,480
- Dr Talbot, Regional Health Authority.
- How are things going?

619
00:38:57,640 --> 00:38:59,120
- We're doing our best.
- Good.

620
00:38:59,280 --> 00:39:02,240
NARRATOR: <i>In the last few days,
emergency headquarters like this</i>

621
00:39:02,400 --> 00:39:04,600
<i>have been hastily improvised
up and down the country</i>

622
00:39:04,760 --> 00:39:07,560
<i>in the basements
of town halls and civic centres.</i>

623
00:39:14,280 --> 00:39:17,520
MAN: <i>The time has now come to make
everything ready for you and your family</i>

624
00:39:17,680 --> 00:39:19,600
<i>in case an air attack happens.</i>

625
00:39:19,760 --> 00:39:22,160
<i>This does not mean
that war is bound to come,</i>

626
00:39:22,320 --> 00:39:25,520
<i>but there is a risk of this
and we must all be prepared for it.</i>

627
00:39:25,680 --> 00:39:27,680
(WARNING SIREN BLARES)

628
00:39:32,120 --> 00:39:36,440
<i>When you hear the attack warning, you
and your family must take cover at once.</i>

629
00:39:38,400 --> 00:39:40,400
<i>Do not stay out of doors.</i>

630
00:39:42,240 --> 00:39:45,120
<i>If you are caught in the open, lie down.</i>

631
00:39:50,200 --> 00:39:52,200
Can you pass us that er...

632
00:39:53,360 --> 00:39:54,800
<i>If you leave your home,</i>

633
00:39:54,960 --> 00:39:58,440
<i>your local authority may take it over
for homeless families,</i>

634
00:39:59,640 --> 00:40:02,080
<i>and if you move,
the authorities in the new place</i>

635
00:40:02,240 --> 00:40:05,920
<i>will not help you with food,
accommodation or other essentials.</i>

636
00:40:06,800 --> 00:40:08,160
(RUTH SOBS)

637
00:40:08,320 --> 00:40:10,800
<i>You are better off in your own home.</i>

638
00:40:12,120 --> 00:40:13,320
<i>Stay there.</i>

639
00:40:29,120 --> 00:40:31,120
(INDISTINCT RADIO SPEECH)

640
00:40:56,320 --> 00:40:58,320
(DOG BARKS IN DISTANCE)

641
00:41:09,080 --> 00:41:12,920
<i>If anyone dies
while you are kept in your fall-out room,</i>

642
00:41:13,720 --> 00:41:16,120
<i>move the body
to another room in the house,</i>

643
00:41:17,240 --> 00:41:20,040
<i>label the body with name and address</i>

644
00:41:20,200 --> 00:41:25,000
<i>and cover it as tightly as possible
in polythene, paper, sheets or blankets.</i>

645
00:41:26,960 --> 00:41:32,080
<i>If, however, you have had a body
in the house for more than five days,</i>

646
00:41:32,240 --> 00:41:34,680
<i>and if it is safe to go outside,</i>

647
00:41:35,400 --> 00:41:38,600
<i>then you should bury the body
for the time being in a trench</i>

648
00:41:38,760 --> 00:41:41,760
<i>or cover it with earth
and mark the spot of the burial.</i>

649
00:41:51,680 --> 00:41:53,680
(RUTH COUGHS AND RETCHES)

650
00:41:58,400 --> 00:42:00,400
(WATER RUNNING)

651
00:42:01,080 --> 00:42:03,880
<i>Here are some ideas
for making your inner refuge.</i>

652
00:42:04,960 --> 00:42:09,400
<i>One: make a lean-to
with sloping doors or strong boards</i>

653
00:42:09,560 --> 00:42:11,480
<i>rested against an inner wall.</i>

654
00:42:11,640 --> 00:42:13,560
You all right, love?

655
00:42:13,720 --> 00:42:15,720
I've just been sick again.

656
00:42:18,840 --> 00:42:22,080
Oh, I feel awful.
I think I'll go back to bed.

657
00:42:23,560 --> 00:42:26,760
Don't worry about it, love.
It'll only last for a week or two.

658
00:42:26,920 --> 00:42:27,920
No.

659
00:42:28,080 --> 00:42:32,160
<i>...close the two open ends with boxes
of earth or sand or heavy furniture.</i>

660
00:42:33,120 --> 00:42:36,080
I'll ring work for you and tell them
you're not coming in.

661
00:42:36,240 --> 00:42:39,840
If there's anybody there.
There were only one or two in yesterday.

662
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:43,520
MRS BECKETT: It's worse than before.
I can't get anything now.

663
00:42:44,120 --> 00:42:47,000
- (SHE PRESSES RECEIVER BUTTON)
- The line's dead.

664
00:42:51,440 --> 00:42:55,760
MR BECKETT: We ought to be getting the
rest of the things out of the cellar now.

665
00:42:58,600 --> 00:43:02,000
<i>The time has now come to make
everything ready for you and your family</i>

666
00:43:02,160 --> 00:43:04,160
<i>in case an air attack happens.</i>

667
00:43:04,880 --> 00:43:07,040
<i>This does not mean
that war is bound to come,</i>

668
00:43:07,200 --> 00:43:10,400
<i>but there is a risk of this
and we must all be prepared for it.</i>

669
00:43:10,560 --> 00:43:12,200
(ELECTRONIC BLEEPING)

670
00:43:12,360 --> 00:43:16,720
<i>When you hear the attack warning, you
and your family must take cover at once.</i>

671
00:43:18,240 --> 00:43:20,240
<i>Do not stay out of doors.</i>

672
00:43:21,560 --> 00:43:23,960
Hello, County.
This is Sheffield District.

673
00:43:24,120 --> 00:43:26,080
Testing, one, two, three, four.

674
00:43:26,240 --> 00:43:28,240
Please report my signal. Over.

675
00:43:28,840 --> 00:43:32,480
Whose bloody responsibility is it, then?
We've all got families.

676
00:43:32,640 --> 00:43:35,520
Look, just get down here.
There's nine other people.

677
00:43:35,680 --> 00:43:38,800
I've got a serious public order problem.

678
00:43:38,960 --> 00:43:42,080
I need at least an extra six PSUs.

679
00:43:42,240 --> 00:43:44,320
Yeah, but when?

680
00:43:44,480 --> 00:43:46,680
Look, I'm using traffic wardens already.

681
00:43:46,840 --> 00:43:48,160
I don't know how many men...

682
00:43:48,320 --> 00:43:51,120
<i>Many of these officers
have had no training at all.</i>

683
00:43:51,280 --> 00:43:54,920
<i>Some have learned of their
emergency role only in the last few days</i>

684
00:43:55,080 --> 00:43:57,680
<i>and almost all are unsure
of their exact duties.</i>

685
00:43:57,840 --> 00:43:59,400
(INDISTINCT DIALOGUE)

686
00:43:59,560 --> 00:44:01,560
I want 56 buses.

687
00:44:02,200 --> 00:44:04,320
I suppose I ought to take
this one off as well.

688
00:44:04,480 --> 00:44:07,200
It'll get scratched to pieces!
It's only just been painted, Bill!

689
00:44:07,360 --> 00:44:09,000
It's better than getting blown to pieces.

690
00:44:09,120 --> 00:44:11,480
Have I to go to school, Mum?
I'm gonna be late.

691
00:44:11,640 --> 00:44:13,320
I don't know. What did it say on t'telly?

692
00:44:13,480 --> 00:44:15,720
I can't remember
whether it said schools were closed.

693
00:44:15,880 --> 00:44:18,880
They are closed. It said so on the news.
We've all to stay at home.

694
00:44:19,040 --> 00:44:20,640
- Are you sure?
- Of course I am!

695
00:44:20,800 --> 00:44:23,520
- They're sending notes out to all parents.
- This is tight!

696
00:44:23,680 --> 00:44:25,840
Great! I had a history test this morning.

697
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:29,400
Alison, go down to Kirby's
and see if they've got any food left.

698
00:44:29,560 --> 00:44:32,480
- Like what?
- Anything - bread, tinned stuff.

699
00:44:32,640 --> 00:44:34,360
Bring what you can. Take my purse.

700
00:44:34,520 --> 00:44:36,360
Dad, are you gonna build
one of these in here?

701
00:44:36,520 --> 00:44:37,640
Over my dead body!

702
00:44:37,800 --> 00:44:42,200
I want to know something more definite
before we start ripping this place to pieces.

703
00:44:42,360 --> 00:44:44,080
- Can I help you?
- Here. Grab hold of that.

704
00:44:44,120 --> 00:44:46,536
- It'll be great. We'll be able to sleep in it.
<i>- ...toilet paper...</i>

705
00:44:46,560 --> 00:44:48,960
- It'll be like going camping.
<i>- ...candles and matches.</i>

706
00:44:49,120 --> 00:44:52,280
<i>The most widespread danger is fall-out.</i>

707
00:44:53,800 --> 00:44:57,600
<i>Fall-out is dust that is sucked up
from the ground by the explosion.</i>

708
00:44:59,600 --> 00:45:01,600
<i>Fall-out can kill.</i>

709
00:45:03,800 --> 00:45:05,640
NARRATOR: <i>It's 8:30am,</i>

710
00:45:05,800 --> 00:45:07,880
<i>3:30 in the morning in Washington.</i>

711
00:45:08,040 --> 00:45:11,160
<i>Over the past four days,
neither the President nor his senior staff</i>

712
00:45:11,320 --> 00:45:13,480
<i>will have had more than a few hours' rest.</i>

713
00:45:13,640 --> 00:45:15,040
<i>This is when they may be asleep.</i>

714
00:45:15,200 --> 00:45:18,040
<i>This is when Western response
will be slowest.</i>

715
00:45:26,600 --> 00:45:29,360
As we expected, nearly all
the supermarket shelves are empty

716
00:45:29,520 --> 00:45:32,760
but we've managed to get the warehouses
controlled by the police.

717
00:45:33,440 --> 00:45:37,640
As yet we haven't located all
the root vegetable clumps on local farms,

718
00:45:37,800 --> 00:45:40,520
but stocks of sugar,
wheat, flour and rice...

719
00:45:40,680 --> 00:45:42,600
- (RAPID BLEEPING)
- ...are quite good.

720
00:45:42,760 --> 00:45:45,040
<i>Attack warning, red!
Attack warning, red!</i>

721
00:45:45,200 --> 00:45:47,760
- Is it for real?
- Attack warning's for bloody real!

722
00:45:47,920 --> 00:45:50,320
Get to your stations.
Come on, move yourselves!

723
00:45:50,480 --> 00:45:52,320
Get that generator going!

724
00:45:52,480 --> 00:45:53,960
Shut the doors!

725
00:45:54,120 --> 00:45:58,400
I want, as soon as you can, every scrap
of information you've got on casualties.

726
00:45:58,560 --> 00:46:00,880
- I must have...
- ...liaison officer.

727
00:46:01,040 --> 00:46:03,480
- (RAPID BLEEPING CONTINUES)
- Get your heads down.

728
00:46:03,640 --> 00:46:06,640
We can't sell you any timber,
you'll have to see t'bosses about it.

729
00:46:06,800 --> 00:46:08,680
It's a bloody joinery, not a timber yard.

730
00:46:08,840 --> 00:46:12,200
- You can't just have a piece of that.
- (WARNING SIREN BLARES)

731
00:46:12,360 --> 00:46:14,360
Ah, come on.

732
00:46:16,240 --> 00:46:18,640
- Come on, quick. Get down!
- (CHILD CRIES)

733
00:46:22,360 --> 00:46:23,960
(SCREAMING AND WAILING)

734
00:46:33,760 --> 00:46:35,480
(SIREN WAILING)

735
00:46:40,320 --> 00:46:42,320
(WARNING SIREN CONTINUES)

736
00:47:00,880 --> 00:47:02,440
These have gone.

737
00:47:02,600 --> 00:47:04,560
- Everything's dead.
- What about t'tellies?

738
00:47:04,720 --> 00:47:08,280
- Why didn't you pull the bloody aerial out?
- Get the standbys working.

739
00:47:08,440 --> 00:47:09,640
Come on.

740
00:47:21,800 --> 00:47:23,600
(SCREAMING)

741
00:47:25,960 --> 00:47:27,800
(TYRES SCREECH)

742
00:47:27,960 --> 00:47:29,040
Bloody hell!

743
00:47:30,240 --> 00:47:32,840
- Hold on, Gordon. You're going too fast!
- (SCREAMING OUTSIDE)

744
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:35,000
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

745
00:47:41,440 --> 00:47:43,440
(WIND WHISTLING)

746
00:47:45,480 --> 00:47:47,360
(GLASS SHATTERING)

747
00:47:47,520 --> 00:47:49,520
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

748
00:47:54,920 --> 00:47:56,640
Come on! Come on!

749
00:48:03,760 --> 00:48:05,960
Come on!
That might just be t'start of it.

750
00:48:06,120 --> 00:48:08,640
(DOGS BARKING, CHILDREN CRYING)

751
00:48:14,160 --> 00:48:16,160
Jesus Christ, they've done it!

752
00:48:20,760 --> 00:48:22,280
They've done it.

753
00:48:24,520 --> 00:48:26,840
- Where are you going?
- To try and get to Ruth,

754
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:29,000
see if she's all right.

755
00:48:31,240 --> 00:48:32,920
Oh, shit!

756
00:48:38,840 --> 00:48:40,560
(SCREAMING)

757
00:48:42,120 --> 00:48:44,000
Come on. Give us a hand with this.

758
00:48:44,160 --> 00:48:46,240
That's all right.
No, that's wrong.

759
00:48:46,400 --> 00:48:47,880
Get all that stuff off.

760
00:48:48,040 --> 00:48:50,680
We've got to get the mattress
on the bottom. That's right.

761
00:48:50,840 --> 00:48:53,560
- Roll it. Put it down there.
- Where is our Alison?

762
00:48:53,720 --> 00:48:55,560
- Build it up.
- This one's on Finningley.

763
00:48:57,200 --> 00:48:59,240
- A ground burst.
- Ground burst.

764
00:48:59,400 --> 00:49:01,400
- Four-three.
- A power station.

765
00:49:03,400 --> 00:49:05,720
Hang on.
There's something on the airport, I think.

766
00:49:11,760 --> 00:49:14,320
(SCREAMING AND COMMOTION)

767
00:49:18,040 --> 00:49:19,920
Shine the torch further down.

768
00:49:20,080 --> 00:49:21,600
Oh, dear.

769
00:49:21,760 --> 00:49:23,840
Ruth, come down here
and give us a hand.

770
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:25,760
MRS BECKETT: Hold the torch, love.

771
00:49:25,920 --> 00:49:27,840
MR BECKETT: Ruth, come and help
your grandmother!

772
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:29,680
MRS BECKETT: Ruth, please!

773
00:49:29,840 --> 00:49:31,320
(COMMOTION)

774
00:49:35,840 --> 00:49:37,760
It'll be all right.

775
00:49:37,920 --> 00:49:39,840
Come on. All this stuff on.

776
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:42,000
Put that on top.

777
00:49:42,640 --> 00:49:43,840
Come on, then.

778
00:49:46,680 --> 00:49:48,680
Ruth! Come on.

779
00:49:50,400 --> 00:49:52,400
- Come on.
- (RUTH SHOUTS OUT)

780
00:50:05,440 --> 00:50:07,440
(BIRDS CHIRP, MICHAEL SOBS)

781
00:50:08,440 --> 00:50:10,240
Michael? Michael!

782
00:50:10,400 --> 00:50:12,400
(SOUNDLESS)

783
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:27,800
(EXPLOSION)

784
00:50:27,960 --> 00:50:29,960
(WIND HOWLS)

785
00:50:43,760 --> 00:50:45,640
(SCREAMING)

786
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:00,000
(FLAMES ROARING)

787
00:51:33,440 --> 00:51:35,440
(WIND HOWLING)

788
00:52:17,280 --> 00:52:18,800
(COUGHING AND SPLUTTERING)

789
00:52:18,960 --> 00:52:22,240
MAN: Take it easy. Don't hurry.
Don't want anybody getting hurt.

790
00:52:23,320 --> 00:52:25,320
Ah, that's the girl. Well done.

791
00:52:26,160 --> 00:52:29,240
It won't be long now till the
lights come on, I suppose.

792
00:52:30,360 --> 00:52:33,360
Well done, Gordon.
How long can you keep that going?

793
00:52:33,520 --> 00:52:35,400
Another two weeks if we're careful.

794
00:52:35,560 --> 00:52:37,480
First-aid kit, quickly.

795
00:52:37,640 --> 00:52:39,640
We've lost County again, I think.

796
00:52:40,320 --> 00:52:43,000
Aerials must have blown.
They were on the roof.

797
00:52:43,720 --> 00:52:45,520
Switch the lights off when you get there.

798
00:52:45,680 --> 00:52:47,520
- Can we raise any districts?
- It's dead.

799
00:52:47,680 --> 00:52:50,080
What about the radio amps?
Can we improvise an aerial?

800
00:52:50,240 --> 00:52:52,520
- We'll try.
- Let's do something quick.

801
00:52:54,320 --> 00:52:57,480
- Where the hell's the first-aid kit?
- It's on the shelf at the back.

802
00:52:57,640 --> 00:53:00,440
It's all blocked down here.
I can't shift a thing.

803
00:53:01,880 --> 00:53:03,760
- How is he?
- He's dead.

804
00:53:03,920 --> 00:53:05,400
I can't find this first-aid kit.

805
00:53:05,560 --> 00:53:08,800
Forget the first-aid kit.
Bring me something to cover him up with.

806
00:53:16,920 --> 00:53:18,600
(SOBBING)

807
00:53:21,400 --> 00:53:23,400
(COUGHING)

808
00:53:25,600 --> 00:53:27,600
- There.
- No! Leave me. (SOBS)

809
00:53:29,520 --> 00:53:31,400
WOMAN: Oh...

810
00:53:31,560 --> 00:53:33,560
Oh, please!

811
00:53:35,400 --> 00:53:37,400
MAN: Help!
WOMAN: Somebody!

812
00:53:38,360 --> 00:53:40,760
(SOBBING AND COUGHING)

813
00:53:44,040 --> 00:53:45,600
(WAILS) No, no!

814
00:53:49,280 --> 00:53:51,280
MAN: Everybody all right?

815
00:53:53,120 --> 00:53:54,560
Mother?

816
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:03,480
(SOBS)

817
00:54:26,560 --> 00:54:28,560
(EXPLOSION, SCREAMING)

818
00:54:30,880 --> 00:54:32,520
(WOMAN CALLS OUT)

819
00:54:32,680 --> 00:54:34,040
(FALLING MASONRY)

820
00:54:34,200 --> 00:54:36,120
Jesus Christ, not another one?

821
00:54:36,280 --> 00:54:38,160
This could go on for ever.

822
00:54:38,320 --> 00:54:40,200
(RADIO STATIC INTERFERENCE)

823
00:54:40,360 --> 00:54:42,680
(VOICE COMMUNICATION CUTS OUT)

824
00:54:43,680 --> 00:54:45,680
It's Stocksbridge police.

825
00:54:46,680 --> 00:54:49,400
- What about rescue?
- Anybody on casualty check?

826
00:54:49,560 --> 00:54:51,480
Is there anything you can do? Over.

827
00:54:51,640 --> 00:54:53,520
Give me another bin liner.

828
00:54:53,680 --> 00:54:55,600
(INDISTINCT RADIO TRAFFIC)

829
00:54:55,760 --> 00:54:57,680
What is your RADIAC reading?

830
00:54:57,840 --> 00:54:59,760
MAN: What about the depot?

831
00:54:59,920 --> 00:55:03,320
I repeat, what is your RADIAC reading?
Over.

832
00:55:04,280 --> 00:55:06,000
(MUFFLED RADIO COMMUNICATIONS)

833
00:55:06,160 --> 00:55:07,440
100.

834
00:55:07,600 --> 00:55:10,720
It's too high.
You've got to get your men under cover.

835
00:55:10,880 --> 00:55:12,880
(ALL TALK AT ONCE)

836
00:55:13,760 --> 00:55:18,240
Can you get us through to
the County Central Headquarters? Over.

837
00:55:18,400 --> 00:55:21,640
WOMAN: Where was that last strike?
- Can you patch us through? Over.

838
00:55:22,720 --> 00:55:25,400
- Stocksbridge, are you receiving me?
- At the fire station.

839
00:55:25,560 --> 00:55:27,560
- Where?
- High Green, I think.

840
00:55:27,720 --> 00:55:29,080
Have you heard anything from them?

841
00:55:29,200 --> 00:55:32,080
Never mind about that.
Ask if they've got casualties.

842
00:55:32,240 --> 00:55:33,480
I can't hear!

843
00:55:34,520 --> 00:55:36,520
We've lost them.

844
00:55:37,240 --> 00:55:39,680
What about Hillsborough
and Stocksbridge?

845
00:55:39,840 --> 00:55:43,200
RADIO: <i>Nothing from Hillsborough,
but Stocksbridge not too bad.</i>

846
00:55:43,360 --> 00:55:45,840
<i>Windows blown in and structural damage
but not too bad.</i>

847
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:47,560
Windows blown in that far out?

848
00:55:47,720 --> 00:55:50,560
- Jesus Christ!
WOMAN: Ask him where that last one was.

849
00:55:50,720 --> 00:55:52,880
Switch that thing off, will you, Gordon?

850
00:55:53,040 --> 00:55:55,040
(COUGHING)

851
00:55:56,840 --> 00:55:59,440
NARRATOR: <i>The first fall-out dust
settles on Sheffield.</i>

852
00:55:59,600 --> 00:56:02,120
<i>It's an hour and 25 minutes
after the attack.</i>

853
00:56:02,760 --> 00:56:05,720
<i>An explosion on the ground at Crewe
has sucked up this debris</i>

854
00:56:05,880 --> 00:56:07,800
<i>and made it radioactive.</i>

855
00:56:07,960 --> 00:56:09,840
<i>The wind has blown it here.</i>

856
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:13,720
<i>This level of attack has broken
most of the windows in Britain.</i>

857
00:56:13,880 --> 00:56:15,640
<i>Many roofs are open to the sky.</i>

858
00:56:15,800 --> 00:56:17,800
<i>Some of the lethal dust gets in.</i>

859
00:56:21,040 --> 00:56:24,280
<i>In these early stages,
the symptoms of radiation sickness</i>

860
00:56:24,440 --> 00:56:26,720
<i>and the symptoms of panic are identical.</i>

861
00:56:33,280 --> 00:56:35,160
(COUGHS AND RETCHES)

862
00:56:37,320 --> 00:56:39,240
(VOMITS)

863
00:56:46,800 --> 00:56:48,800
You all right, Ruth?

864
00:56:49,880 --> 00:56:51,040
Ruth?

865
00:56:52,320 --> 00:56:54,240
I couldn't help it.

866
00:56:54,400 --> 00:56:56,320
It just came on.

867
00:56:56,480 --> 00:56:59,120
Don't worry about it, love.
It's not your fault.

868
00:56:59,280 --> 00:57:02,600
- We've all got it.
- I know, but I'm so ashamed.

869
00:57:02,760 --> 00:57:03,960
Yes, I know, love.

870
00:57:04,120 --> 00:57:06,616
- Messing the bed at my age.
- It's the shock, isn't it, Gordon?

871
00:57:06,640 --> 00:57:08,560
It's like being a little baby again.

872
00:57:08,720 --> 00:57:10,640
Lie down.

873
00:57:10,800 --> 00:57:12,800
Ruth, come and help me
clean Grandma up.

874
00:57:12,960 --> 00:57:14,680
Ruth, be careful with that, love.

875
00:57:14,840 --> 00:57:17,160
You don't know how long
it's gonna have to last us.

876
00:57:17,320 --> 00:57:20,520
MR BECKETT: Ruth, don't just sit there.
Do something for once!

877
00:57:20,680 --> 00:57:22,680
(COUGHING)

878
00:57:26,240 --> 00:57:28,240
Oh! Ooh!

879
00:57:35,560 --> 00:57:37,480
- (COUGHING)
MRS KEMP: Michael.

880
00:57:37,640 --> 00:57:40,080
Michael... I've got to find him, Bill.

881
00:57:40,240 --> 00:57:42,160
MR KEMP: You stop here.

882
00:57:42,320 --> 00:57:45,080
MRS KEMP: I've got to find him.
MR KEMP: I'll go and look for him.

883
00:57:45,240 --> 00:57:47,160
You stop here, love.

884
00:57:47,320 --> 00:57:49,240
I'll only be out a few minutes.

885
00:57:49,400 --> 00:57:51,536
- (SHE COUGHS)
- Stop here, love, please. I'll go look.

886
00:57:51,560 --> 00:57:53,560
No, I've got to come. No.

887
00:57:54,440 --> 00:57:56,320
- Help me.
- All right.

888
00:57:56,480 --> 00:57:58,480
(COUGHING)

889
00:58:00,120 --> 00:58:01,840
Oh, my God.

890
00:58:05,520 --> 00:58:06,800
Michael?

891
00:58:06,960 --> 00:58:08,600
Michael!

892
00:58:11,080 --> 00:58:12,880
(COUGHING)

893
00:58:24,360 --> 00:58:26,080
(SHE SOBS)

894
00:58:34,560 --> 00:58:36,160
(HE COUGHS)

895
00:58:43,840 --> 00:58:46,160
We haven't heard from County HQ
for two days.

896
00:58:46,320 --> 00:58:48,240
RADIO: <i>They are still here!</i>

897
00:58:48,400 --> 00:58:50,400
Well, who the hell else have you tried?

898
00:58:50,560 --> 00:58:53,960
<i>- All of them, but nothing back yet.
</i>-Send another motorcycle!

899
00:58:54,120 --> 00:58:55,560
There are no roads left.

900
00:58:55,720 --> 00:58:59,040
All the people here will be dead already.
It's completely flattened.

901
00:58:59,760 --> 00:59:04,280
Round here 50 per cent will still be alive
but here they're as good as dead already.

902
00:59:04,440 --> 00:59:06,760
They've probably received a lethal dose.

903
00:59:08,920 --> 00:59:11,360
- What about here?
- It'll be pretty heavy there.

904
00:59:11,520 --> 00:59:16,440
If the wind's still blowing up from the west,
southwest, it's in direct line from Crewe.

905
00:59:17,280 --> 00:59:21,000
Oh, 800 rads, 1,000... difficult to say.

906
00:59:21,880 --> 00:59:24,160
Depends what sort of cover they've built,
of course.

907
00:59:24,320 --> 00:59:27,920
- If they've got a decent cellar...
- You're wanted on the radio.

908
00:59:34,480 --> 00:59:36,400
There's no way of getting anything out.

909
00:59:36,560 --> 00:59:37,920
According to the... Listen.

910
00:59:38,080 --> 00:59:40,000
Yeah. Yes, I'll pass the message on.

911
00:59:40,160 --> 00:59:43,200
There's no bloody roads at all.
What am I expected to do?

912
00:59:43,360 --> 00:59:44,840
(ALL SHOUT AT ONCE)

913
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:47,560
I know about that
but I can't get anything out, can I?

914
00:59:47,720 --> 00:59:49,240
...some list of vehicles?

915
00:59:49,400 --> 00:59:50,640
Listen.

916
00:59:50,800 --> 00:59:53,720
'Ey, I've got a message
from Rivelin Valley police.

917
00:59:54,520 --> 00:59:57,680
They've managed to get through
to Beauchief works depot.

918
00:59:57,840 --> 01:00:01,640
They've got some vehicles on the road
but they're nearly out of fuel.

919
01:00:01,800 --> 01:00:04,000
What the bloody hell
have they been doing with it all?

920
01:00:04,160 --> 01:00:08,600
They didn't tell me. They just said they
want to know where they can get some more.

921
01:00:08,760 --> 01:00:10,760
- And they've got no food.
- Oh, God.

922
01:00:11,320 --> 01:00:13,960
- Look, I've got...
- Just let me get on with it, OK?

923
01:00:35,240 --> 01:00:37,240
(WIND BLOWING)

924
01:00:45,960 --> 01:00:48,640
Here you are, Mother.
Something to eat for you.

925
01:00:50,680 --> 01:00:53,080
Better leave her.
The rest'll do her good.

926
01:00:53,880 --> 01:00:55,880
Well, at least it won't go cold.

927
01:00:58,960 --> 01:01:00,680
- Ruth.
- (RUTH SOBS)

928
01:01:01,760 --> 01:01:03,680
Ruth, love.

929
01:01:03,840 --> 01:01:06,360
Come on, love.
You'll have to eat something.

930
01:01:07,200 --> 01:01:09,960
But you'll have to, love.
It's not just you now, you know.

931
01:01:10,120 --> 01:01:12,040
The baby needs some food as well.

932
01:01:12,200 --> 01:01:14,840
- Come on.
- I don't care about this baby any more.

933
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:16,920
- Oh, Ruth.
- I wish it was dead.

934
01:01:17,080 --> 01:01:18,640
Don't say things like that.

935
01:01:18,800 --> 01:01:21,640
There's no point.
There's no point with Jimmy dead.

936
01:01:21,800 --> 01:01:25,920
- But you don't know he'd dead, love.
- He is! He is! I know he is!

937
01:01:26,080 --> 01:01:27,800
You can't be certain.

938
01:01:27,960 --> 01:01:32,120
We're breathing in all this radiation
all the time.

939
01:01:32,280 --> 01:01:34,360
My baby.

940
01:01:34,520 --> 01:01:37,680
(RUTH SOBS)
It'll be ugly and deformed.

941
01:01:37,840 --> 01:01:39,840
(SHE SOBS)

942
01:01:41,400 --> 01:01:42,640
(WIND WHISTLING)

943
01:01:42,800 --> 01:01:44,800
(DOG BARKING)

944
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:49,920
MRS KEMP: Oh, Michael.

945
01:01:50,080 --> 01:01:52,000
And Alison and Jimmy.

946
01:01:52,160 --> 01:01:54,920
- All of them gone.
- (COUGHING)

947
01:01:56,360 --> 01:01:58,000
Alison...

948
01:01:58,160 --> 01:02:00,160
Alison and Michael...

949
01:02:01,680 --> 01:02:03,080
All dead.

950
01:02:03,240 --> 01:02:05,800
No. We... We don't know that.

951
01:02:06,520 --> 01:02:09,120
They might be... might be safe somewhere.

952
01:02:10,080 --> 01:02:12,080
Only I wish I were dead.

953
01:02:12,960 --> 01:02:14,880
I wish it were me.

954
01:02:15,040 --> 01:02:17,040
(HE SOBS)

955
01:02:21,360 --> 01:02:24,440
(SOBBING)
I wish I could swap places with him.

956
01:02:30,360 --> 01:02:32,280
Right. Let's get in.

957
01:02:32,440 --> 01:02:34,440
Watch that bloody water.

958
01:02:38,080 --> 01:02:39,840
How far does this go back?

959
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:43,600
If bloody four floors have come down on this
lot, it could go back for yards and yards.

960
01:02:44,760 --> 01:02:46,760
(HE EXHALES NOISILY)

961
01:02:48,400 --> 01:02:50,040
Try it again, Gordon.

962
01:02:51,160 --> 01:02:54,280
Still nothing coming through.
It must be blocked further up.

963
01:02:55,360 --> 01:02:57,600
How much stuff
do you think's on top of us?

964
01:02:57,760 --> 01:02:59,640
<i>Most of t'town hall, I should think.</i>

965
01:02:59,800 --> 01:03:01,840
Well, when will you be able to get to us?

966
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:04,800
<i>- I can't get lifting gear through.
</i>-What about the army, the military?

967
01:03:04,960 --> 01:03:07,040
<i>There's no way through!
The roads are just blocked!</i>

968
01:03:07,200 --> 01:03:08,560
We've not heard from County yet.

969
01:03:08,720 --> 01:03:12,600
If we don't hear sometime soon,
we'll never get things under control.

970
01:03:12,760 --> 01:03:15,040
You try getting through to them.
It's bloody hopeless.

971
01:03:15,200 --> 01:03:19,640
- I've got starving mobs in Ecclesfield...
- Look, it's not our decision anyway.

972
01:03:19,800 --> 01:03:22,720
It's up to Zonal to authorise release
of buffer stocks

973
01:03:22,880 --> 01:03:25,800
- and then it becomes a County decision.
- We can't get through to County!

974
01:03:25,920 --> 01:03:27,640
Are we going to let them starve?

975
01:03:27,800 --> 01:03:29,896
- Even if we did have the authority...
- We're on our own.

976
01:03:29,920 --> 01:03:32,681
You've got the authority. About
bloody time you did something with it!

977
01:03:32,720 --> 01:03:35,720
What's the point of wasting food
on people who are going to die anyway?

978
01:03:35,880 --> 01:03:38,880
I agree with Clive.
The food stocks are not gonna last long.

979
01:03:39,040 --> 01:03:40,720
A lot of people just didn't stock up.

980
01:03:40,880 --> 01:03:42,520
How could they?
The shops were empty.

981
01:03:42,680 --> 01:03:44,240
Now they're coming out of the shelters.

982
01:03:44,400 --> 01:03:48,040
I know it sounds callous but we should
hang on to the little food we've got.

983
01:03:48,200 --> 01:03:51,000
SHARON:
I need that food to force people to work.

984
01:03:51,160 --> 01:03:54,120
RADIO: <i>There's about 2,000 of them
outside Roxburgh fire station.</i>

985
01:03:54,280 --> 01:03:56,160
Go make us a cup of tea, Sharon.

986
01:03:56,320 --> 01:03:58,440
Go make it yourself.
I'm not your bloody wife!

987
01:03:58,600 --> 01:04:00,520
Anybody got a fag?

988
01:04:00,680 --> 01:04:02,680
(INDISTINCT RADIO SPEECH)

989
01:04:05,720 --> 01:04:07,360
Bad for your health, you know.

990
01:04:07,520 --> 01:04:09,120
<i>They're pulling the place apart.</i>

991
01:04:09,880 --> 01:04:12,480
Look, I don't care
how much trouble they're causing.

992
01:04:12,640 --> 01:04:15,640
We're not sending our men in there
with radiation as high as that.

993
01:04:15,800 --> 01:04:17,720
I know that but what's the point?

994
01:04:17,880 --> 01:04:20,280
They're all gonna die on that patch anyway.

995
01:04:20,840 --> 01:04:24,160
Bill, just get... get... get me a drink.

996
01:04:24,320 --> 01:04:25,920
Please, a drink.

997
01:04:26,080 --> 01:04:29,000
I'll see if I can...
see if I can find anything.

998
01:04:32,920 --> 01:04:34,000
I won't...

999
01:04:34,160 --> 01:04:36,160
I won't be long.

1000
01:04:38,840 --> 01:04:40,840
(SHE RETCHES AND COUGHS)

1001
01:04:43,120 --> 01:04:45,000
(SPLUTTERS AND RETCHES)

1002
01:04:50,400 --> 01:04:52,400
(HE COUGHS)

1003
01:04:54,480 --> 01:04:56,480
(RASPING COUGH)

1004
01:05:18,440 --> 01:05:20,440
(HE SOBS)

1005
01:05:24,840 --> 01:05:26,760
Just a minute. Just a minute.

1006
01:05:26,920 --> 01:05:28,920
(STRAINING)

1007
01:05:33,680 --> 01:05:35,600
That's it. That's it.

1008
01:05:35,760 --> 01:05:37,960
- Just a minute, love.
- For God's sake.

1009
01:05:39,680 --> 01:05:41,360
That's it.

1010
01:05:42,640 --> 01:05:44,560
Oh, God.

1011
01:05:44,720 --> 01:05:47,320
- Oh, look at it.
- Just a minute. Just a minute.

1012
01:05:50,680 --> 01:05:52,680
(STRAINING) Oh.

1013
01:05:53,520 --> 01:05:55,520
Can you manage that?

1014
01:05:57,760 --> 01:06:00,680
All right, put her down here a minute.
Put her down here.

1015
01:06:00,840 --> 01:06:02,760
Give us one of the blankets.

1016
01:06:06,320 --> 01:06:07,640
Come on.

1017
01:06:07,800 --> 01:06:09,120
Oh, my God.

1018
01:06:13,840 --> 01:06:15,200
Ruth?

1019
01:06:15,880 --> 01:06:17,040
- Ruth!
- Ruth!

1020
01:06:18,280 --> 01:06:20,280
(SOBBING) Ruth!

1021
01:06:21,680 --> 01:06:23,200
Ruth!

1022
01:06:23,360 --> 01:06:24,920
(SOBS)

1023
01:06:28,240 --> 01:06:30,160
Come on, down you go.

1024
01:06:30,320 --> 01:06:32,120
Careful.

1025
01:06:56,680 --> 01:06:58,760
(WIND HOWLING)

1026
01:07:02,000 --> 01:07:04,600
RADIO: <i>Radiation levels
are still dangerous.</i>

1027
01:07:04,760 --> 01:07:09,880
<i>Residents of Release Band A,
that is Woodspring and Abbeydale,</i>

1028
01:07:10,040 --> 01:07:13,640
<i>should not stay out of their shelters
for more than two hours per day.</i>

1029
01:07:13,800 --> 01:07:18,640
<i>Residents of Release Band B, that is
Nether Edge, Thornycroft and Broomhill,</i>

1030
01:07:18,800 --> 01:07:20,600
<i>no longer than one hour per day.</i>

1031
01:07:20,760 --> 01:07:22,680
(WATER BABBLING)

1032
01:07:22,840 --> 01:07:24,840
(WIND HOWLING)

1033
01:07:27,720 --> 01:07:29,320
(HE COUGHS)

1034
01:07:36,600 --> 01:07:38,120
(HE SLURPS)

1035
01:08:06,000 --> 01:08:07,600
Mandy!

1036
01:08:07,760 --> 01:08:09,360
Mandy?

1037
01:08:10,240 --> 01:08:12,160
Have you seen our Mandy?

1038
01:08:12,920 --> 01:08:14,320
Mandy?

1039
01:08:15,240 --> 01:08:16,720
Mandy?

1040
01:08:17,280 --> 01:08:19,280
BOY: Mum! Mum!

1041
01:08:20,760 --> 01:08:21,840
Mum!

1042
01:08:22,920 --> 01:08:24,000
Mum! Mum!

1043
01:08:24,160 --> 01:08:25,360
Mum!

1044
01:10:03,600 --> 01:10:05,320
MRS BECKETT: What time is it?

1045
01:10:07,120 --> 01:10:09,120
Half-past two.

1046
01:10:11,200 --> 01:10:13,120
Night... Night or day?

1047
01:10:13,280 --> 01:10:15,280
Night, I think.

1048
01:10:16,360 --> 01:10:18,200
I'm not sure.

1049
01:10:18,360 --> 01:10:19,840
I'm losing track.

1050
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:22,680
I'm not sure
whether it's night or day any more.

1051
01:10:24,000 --> 01:10:26,000
(FAINT CLATTERING)

1052
01:10:58,080 --> 01:11:00,680
NARRATOR: <i>Hanging in the atmosphere,
the clouds of debris</i>

1053
01:11:00,840 --> 01:11:02,840
<i>shut out the sun's heat and light.</i>

1054
01:11:03,680 --> 01:11:07,480
<i>Across large areas of the Northern
Hemisphere, it starts to get dark,</i>

1055
01:11:07,640 --> 01:11:09,640
<i>it starts to get cold.</i>

1056
01:11:10,400 --> 01:11:13,640
<i>In the centres of large land masses
like America or Russia,</i>

1057
01:11:13,800 --> 01:11:18,320
<i>the temperature drop may be severe,
as much as 25 degrees centigrade.</i>

1058
01:11:19,520 --> 01:11:21,640
<i>Even in Britain, within days of the attack,</i>

1059
01:11:21,800 --> 01:11:25,440
<i>it could fall to freezing or below
for long, dark periods.</i>

1060
01:11:30,160 --> 01:11:32,160
(WIND HOWLING)

1061
01:12:00,880 --> 01:12:02,880
(ANGRY SHOUTING)

1062
01:12:11,280 --> 01:12:13,360
Go back to your homes.

1063
01:12:13,520 --> 01:12:16,640
Allocation of foodstuff will begin shortly.

1064
01:12:17,200 --> 01:12:20,000
The distribution points will be announced.

1065
01:12:20,160 --> 01:12:24,400
I repeat, go home.
There is nothing we can do.

1066
01:12:24,760 --> 01:12:27,320
We have no authority to distribute food.

1067
01:12:27,480 --> 01:12:28,880
Who are you saving it for?

1068
01:12:29,560 --> 01:12:31,120
This is a warning.

1069
01:12:31,280 --> 01:12:36,000
Any attempt to appropriate provisions
from these premises will be met by force.

1070
01:12:36,160 --> 01:12:40,520
So I advise you to disperse
and go back to your homes.

1071
01:12:41,200 --> 01:12:43,200
WOMAN: I want to eat!

1072
01:12:44,640 --> 01:12:46,080
Prepare to fire gas.

1073
01:12:46,240 --> 01:12:47,760
(CLAMOURING)

1074
01:12:54,560 --> 01:12:56,960
One round CS gas, straight at gates.

1075
01:13:00,600 --> 01:13:02,040
(SCREAMING)

1076
01:13:02,840 --> 01:13:04,840
One round at that man.

1077
01:13:06,400 --> 01:13:07,880
(SCREAMING)

1078
01:13:10,600 --> 01:13:12,600
(PANICKED CRIES)

1079
01:13:16,640 --> 01:13:18,640
(COUGHING AND SPLUTTERING)

1080
01:13:35,640 --> 01:13:37,640
(MOANING AND WAILING)

1081
01:13:46,680 --> 01:13:49,960
NARRATOR: <i>The entire peacetime
resources of the British health service,</i>

1082
01:13:50,120 --> 01:13:51,400
<i>even if they survived,</i>

1083
01:13:51,560 --> 01:13:55,760
<i>would be unable to cope with the effects of
even the single bomb that's hit Sheffield.</i>

1084
01:13:56,760 --> 01:13:59,200
MAN: David?
2ND MAN: Bill!

1085
01:14:09,520 --> 01:14:11,520
(PEOPLE SHOUT OUT VARIOUS NAMES)

1086
01:14:15,560 --> 01:14:17,560
(WOMAN SOBBING)

1087
01:14:21,640 --> 01:14:24,600
WOMAN: Rosie? Rosie?

1088
01:14:25,560 --> 01:14:27,000
Diane?

1089
01:14:28,280 --> 01:14:30,280
(COUGHING AND MOANING)

1090
01:14:39,040 --> 01:14:40,760
(RASPING COUGH)

1091
01:14:46,560 --> 01:14:48,520
(COUGHING AND SPLUTTERING)

1092
01:14:48,680 --> 01:14:50,680
(PIERCING SHRIEK)

1093
01:14:58,040 --> 01:14:59,400
Listen...

1094
01:15:03,880 --> 01:15:05,800
(MAN GROANS IN AGONY)

1095
01:15:05,960 --> 01:15:07,960
(WAILING AND MOANING)

1096
01:15:09,720 --> 01:15:11,280
(SHRIEKING)

1097
01:15:12,000 --> 01:15:13,560
NURSE: We can't do anything.

1098
01:15:13,720 --> 01:15:15,640
WOMAN: Please! Please!

1099
01:15:15,800 --> 01:15:17,600
(CLAMOURING)

1100
01:15:17,760 --> 01:15:20,320
(CHILD SCREAMS)

1101
01:15:23,840 --> 01:15:25,000
(SOBBING)

1102
01:15:26,080 --> 01:15:27,480
(HE WHIMPERS)

1103
01:15:31,080 --> 01:15:32,800
(SCREAMS IN AGONY)

1104
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:35,440
(COUGHING)

1105
01:15:36,120 --> 01:15:39,560
NARRATOR: <i>By this time,
without drugs, water or bandages,</i>

1106
01:15:40,120 --> 01:15:42,880
<i>without electricity
or medical support facilities,</i>

1107
01:15:43,040 --> 01:15:46,320
<i>there is virtually no way
a doctor can exercise his skill.</i>

1108
01:15:46,840 --> 01:15:51,920
<i>As a source of help or comfort, he is little
better equipped than the nearest survivor.</i>

1109
01:15:54,320 --> 01:15:56,120
CHILD: I don't like it!

1110
01:15:56,840 --> 01:15:58,840
I don't like it!

1111
01:15:59,800 --> 01:16:02,320
Mum! Dad!

1112
01:16:03,760 --> 01:16:05,160
Mama!

1113
01:16:06,640 --> 01:16:08,640
Ma!

1114
01:16:26,200 --> 01:16:28,080
We've no choice, as far as I can see.

1115
01:16:28,240 --> 01:16:30,800
- Can't we get any food from outside?
- Where from?

1116
01:16:30,960 --> 01:16:33,720
We've told County and everybody's in
the same boat, aren't they?

1117
01:16:33,880 --> 01:16:38,080
Trouble is, we can't contact Rockley or
Airesbrook. God knows what's happened.

1118
01:16:38,240 --> 01:16:40,160
Probably been raided.

1119
01:16:40,320 --> 01:16:42,240
What do you think, Doctor?

1120
01:16:42,400 --> 01:16:44,320
We'll have to cut their rations.

1121
01:16:44,480 --> 01:16:46,000
I've worked it out there.

1122
01:16:46,160 --> 01:16:49,640
1,000 calories for manual workers
and 500 for the rest.

1123
01:16:49,800 --> 01:16:51,480
500?

1124
01:16:51,640 --> 01:16:54,720
500? That wouldn't keep a flea alive!

1125
01:16:55,360 --> 01:16:58,200
Should we be bothering to keep
anybody alive if they can't work?

1126
01:16:58,360 --> 01:17:00,360
A lot of people are gonna die anyway.

1127
01:17:01,760 --> 01:17:04,360
It's back to survival of the
fittest, I suppose.

1128
01:17:04,520 --> 01:17:07,320
What is that in terms of food, then,
500 calories?

1129
01:17:08,640 --> 01:17:09,920
I don't know...

1130
01:17:10,080 --> 01:17:11,960
a few slices of bread...

1131
01:17:12,120 --> 01:17:13,760
some soup...

1132
01:17:13,920 --> 01:17:15,840
a lamb chop...

1133
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:17,920
a treacle tart...

1134
01:17:18,080 --> 01:17:20,000
a few pints of beer.

1135
01:17:20,160 --> 01:17:22,160
(CHUCKLES)

1136
01:17:24,160 --> 01:17:26,160
Bastards!

1137
01:17:27,680 --> 01:17:30,160
Look, you must have an empty factory
somewhere to put them!

1138
01:17:30,320 --> 01:17:31,480
No, you look!

1139
01:17:31,640 --> 01:17:34,400
I've got thousands of homeless people
up there walking around.

1140
01:17:34,560 --> 01:17:37,600
I've got enough on with them
without worrying about bloody criminals!

1141
01:17:37,760 --> 01:17:39,640
You're gonna have to find
somewhere to put 'em!

1142
01:17:39,800 --> 01:17:43,080
Well, I don't know!
Look, shoot the buggers. I don't care!

1143
01:17:44,520 --> 01:17:46,920
SHARON: Can we get a water tank
to Broomhill?

1144
01:17:47,080 --> 01:17:49,080
The standpipe's run dry.

1145
01:17:51,520 --> 01:17:54,840
Oh, Christ, Steve.
This should have been sorted out days ago.

1146
01:17:55,000 --> 01:17:57,920
What about the rest centres? Can we not
tell them to make their way there?

1147
01:17:58,080 --> 01:18:01,080
No, there'll be no point.
They'll be overrun anyway.

1148
01:18:02,800 --> 01:18:04,560
What about tents?

1149
01:18:04,720 --> 01:18:06,640
Got any tents we could use?

1150
01:18:06,800 --> 01:18:08,080
Tents?

1151
01:18:08,240 --> 01:18:10,160
How the hell should I know?

1152
01:18:10,320 --> 01:18:13,840
If you want to know about tents,
go and phone the bloody Boy Scouts!

1153
01:18:14,000 --> 01:18:16,960
Piss off, will you?
You're not the only one under pressure!

1154
01:18:17,120 --> 01:18:19,120
- I bloody know!
- You sort it!

1155
01:18:20,120 --> 01:18:24,200
And what the hell are you doing about
digging us out? That's what I'd like to know.

1156
01:18:30,680 --> 01:18:32,680
(RATS SQUEAKING)

1157
01:18:55,920 --> 01:18:57,920
(DOOR OPENS)

1158
01:18:59,360 --> 01:19:00,680
(COUGHING)

1159
01:19:00,840 --> 01:19:02,760
Bloody hell, what a stink!

1160
01:19:02,920 --> 01:19:04,920
Let's get out of here. I'm gonna puke!

1161
01:19:05,080 --> 01:19:07,080
(COUGHING)

1162
01:19:18,040 --> 01:19:20,040
SOLDIER: Halt or I'll fire!

1163
01:19:20,880 --> 01:19:23,160
Number three,
a round for that man over there!

1164
01:19:23,320 --> 01:19:25,280
(GUNSHOT)

1165
01:19:26,640 --> 01:19:28,320
Number one, go in and search the house.

1166
01:19:28,480 --> 01:19:30,000
Up against the wall.

1167
01:19:30,160 --> 01:19:32,800
- We weren't doing anything.
- Do you know the penalty for looting?

1168
01:19:32,960 --> 01:19:35,440
- I ain't looting, searching empty houses!
- Quiet!

1169
01:19:35,600 --> 01:19:37,080
- Shut up!
- What choice have we got?

1170
01:19:37,240 --> 01:19:39,280
- We were hungry!
- What else can we do?

1171
01:19:39,440 --> 01:19:42,440
- We're starving!
- Two bodies in the cellar, man and woman.

1172
01:19:42,600 --> 01:19:45,480
- The man's had his head battered in.
- They were like that when we came!

1173
01:19:45,640 --> 01:19:47,000
It were him!

1174
01:19:47,160 --> 01:19:49,080
- Out.
- We ain't done nothing!

1175
01:19:49,240 --> 01:19:51,200
Number two, pick up the stolen goods.

1176
01:19:51,360 --> 01:19:53,360
We ain't done anything!

1177
01:20:00,880 --> 01:20:04,800
- We were only after a bit of food.
- Check the house and search the body.

1178
01:20:10,200 --> 01:20:12,360
- Bag of crisps.
- What flavour are they?

1179
01:20:12,520 --> 01:20:15,480
- Prawn cocktail.
- They fucking would be. I hate them.

1180
01:20:15,640 --> 01:20:17,640
Come on.

1181
01:20:24,360 --> 01:20:26,360
(DOG WHINES)

1182
01:20:29,160 --> 01:20:32,840
RADIO: <i>All able-bodied citizens,
men, women and children,</i>

1183
01:20:33,000 --> 01:20:34,920
<i>should report for reconstruction duties</i>

1184
01:20:35,080 --> 01:20:37,600
<i>commencing 0800 hours
tomorrow morning.</i>

1185
01:20:38,400 --> 01:20:41,640
<i>The inhabitants of Release Band F,
that is Dore and Totley,</i>

1186
01:20:41,800 --> 01:20:45,480
<i>Abbeydale and Woodseats,
should rendezvous in Abbeydale Park.</i>

1187
01:20:46,600 --> 01:20:48,600
<i>Release Band В, that is...</i>

1188
01:20:48,760 --> 01:20:51,400
NARRATOR: <i>Money has had no meaning
since the attack.</i>

1189
01:20:51,560 --> 01:20:54,880
<i>The only viable currency is food,
given as reward for work,</i>

1190
01:20:55,040 --> 01:20:57,040
<i>or withheld as punishment.</i>

1191
01:20:57,920 --> 01:21:01,680
<i>In the grim economics of the aftermath,
there are two harsh realities:</i>

1192
01:21:02,440 --> 01:21:05,640
<i>a survivor who can work
gets more food than one who can't,</i>

1193
01:21:05,800 --> 01:21:08,880
<i>and the more who die,
the more food is left for the rest.</i>

1194
01:21:15,160 --> 01:21:17,160
(COUGHS)

1195
01:21:20,840 --> 01:21:23,360
I could murder a fag now.

1196
01:21:24,160 --> 01:21:26,640
I used to love a fag after a meal.

1197
01:21:28,440 --> 01:21:30,440
Have you got owt to swap?

1198
01:21:31,920 --> 01:21:33,920
I've got some Scotch.

1199
01:21:38,160 --> 01:21:39,760
(COUGHS)

1200
01:21:44,520 --> 01:21:46,520
Ohh. Bloody hell.

1201
01:21:54,920 --> 01:21:56,720
(COUGHS)

1202
01:22:08,520 --> 01:22:10,240
(COUGHS)

1203
01:22:16,360 --> 01:22:18,360
(ELECTRONIC GAME BLEEPS)

1204
01:22:29,920 --> 01:22:31,720
(GROANS)

1205
01:22:41,520 --> 01:22:43,320
(SOBS)

1206
01:23:21,000 --> 01:23:23,000
(CLAMOURING)

1207
01:23:24,080 --> 01:23:27,000
NARRATOR: <i>Detention camps
are improvised to cope with looters.</i>

1208
01:23:27,160 --> 01:23:28,720
<i>Their numbers are growing.</i>

1209
01:23:30,120 --> 01:23:32,040
(SHOUTING)

1210
01:23:32,200 --> 01:23:34,040
Let me out!

1211
01:23:34,200 --> 01:23:35,600
Bastard!

1212
01:23:35,760 --> 01:23:38,040
WOMAN: Let us out!

1213
01:23:38,200 --> 01:23:41,000
Buggered if I'm gonna be shot
by a traffic warden!

1214
01:23:41,800 --> 01:23:43,400
Let us out!

1215
01:23:43,560 --> 01:23:45,680
(HEAVY BREATHING
THROUGH APPARATUS)

1216
01:23:45,840 --> 01:23:47,840
(MUFFLED DIALOGUE)

1217
01:23:51,480 --> 01:23:53,760
- Watch yourselves here, lads.
- Right.

1218
01:23:54,520 --> 01:23:56,520
Shine that light down here, quick.

1219
01:23:57,480 --> 01:23:59,560
Watch the girder. Come on, over here.

1220
01:24:01,880 --> 01:24:03,760
- OK?
- Yep.

1221
01:24:05,080 --> 01:24:07,080
(HEAVY THUD)

1222
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:15,800
- Over here.
- Another one over here.

1223
01:24:15,960 --> 01:24:17,840
Another one over there.

1224
01:24:18,000 --> 01:24:19,920
How many altogether?

1225
01:24:20,080 --> 01:24:22,080
About four, five, six.

1226
01:24:23,320 --> 01:24:24,880
(HEAVY BREATHING)

1227
01:24:31,680 --> 01:24:33,680
(RATS SQUEAKING)

1228
01:24:50,960 --> 01:24:52,960
(FLIES BUZZING)

1229
01:25:21,560 --> 01:25:23,560
(TWO GUNSHOTS)

1230
01:25:49,800 --> 01:25:52,880
NARRATOR: <i>A growing exodus from cities
in search of food.</i>

1231
01:25:54,480 --> 01:25:55,840
<i>Its July.</i>

1232
01:25:56,000 --> 01:25:59,600
<i>The countryside is cold
and full of unknown radiation hazards.</i>

1233
01:26:00,640 --> 01:26:02,840
<i>By now, five to six weeks after the attack,</i>

1234
01:26:03,000 --> 01:26:06,600
<i>deaths from the effects of fall-out
are approaching their peak.</i>

1235
01:26:06,760 --> 01:26:08,760
(COUGHING AND WHEEZING)

1236
01:26:11,600 --> 01:26:13,560
(RETCHING)

1237
01:26:53,800 --> 01:26:55,800
(AEROPLANE ROARS OVERHEAD)

1238
01:26:57,040 --> 01:26:59,040
MAN ON PLANE:
Return to your homes!

1239
01:26:59,800 --> 01:27:01,800
Return to your homes.

1240
01:27:02,760 --> 01:27:04,760
(ANGRY SHOUTING)

1241
01:27:06,080 --> 01:27:08,080
Return to your homes.

1242
01:27:09,000 --> 01:27:11,680
Turn back. Turn back.

1243
01:27:23,640 --> 01:27:25,640
Right, down there.

1244
01:27:28,720 --> 01:27:30,720
Keep going.

1245
01:27:32,920 --> 01:27:34,920
Come on.

1246
01:27:41,720 --> 01:27:43,720
(KNOCKING)

1247
01:27:45,040 --> 01:27:46,680
- George Langley?
- Yes, what do you want?

1248
01:27:46,760 --> 01:27:48,800
You've been designated
four temporary residents.

1249
01:27:48,960 --> 01:27:50,960
I'm having no strangers
coming to live here.

1250
01:27:51,120 --> 01:27:53,440
You've no choice.
It's law under the new Emergency...

1251
01:27:53,600 --> 01:27:57,400
I don't care what it is. This is my house
and I'm having no strangers in it.

1252
01:27:57,560 --> 01:28:00,000
According to my records,
you've got four spare rooms.

1253
01:28:00,160 --> 01:28:02,240
Aye, and they're stopping spare an' all.

1254
01:28:02,400 --> 01:28:05,920
They can't just come here and walk
into people's houses. It's not right.

1255
01:28:06,080 --> 01:28:08,840
We're not here to argue the rights
and wrongs of the matter.

1256
01:28:09,000 --> 01:28:10,920
- You four...
- Besides, it's bloody dangerous!

1257
01:28:11,080 --> 01:28:13,520
They might bring
all sorts of diseases with them!

1258
01:28:13,680 --> 01:28:16,120
- Come on, in you go.
- They might be contaminated!

1259
01:28:16,280 --> 01:28:18,600
- In you go, first four.
- Well, look at him. Look at him!

1260
01:28:18,760 --> 01:28:21,360
- Look at him.
- That's enough. Go on, in you go.

1261
01:28:23,360 --> 01:28:24,960
OLD MAN: You've no right there.

1262
01:28:25,120 --> 01:28:26,760
Right, number 19.

1263
01:28:29,960 --> 01:28:31,840
(GLASS SHATTERING, GUNSHOT)

1264
01:28:32,000 --> 01:28:34,960
OLD MAN: Get out, will you?
The whole lot of you.

1265
01:28:35,120 --> 01:28:37,520
- Go on!
- You've no right just to throw us...

1266
01:28:37,680 --> 01:28:39,600
MAN: We're going.

1267
01:28:39,760 --> 01:28:41,840
2ND MAN: We've nowhere else to go.

1268
01:28:42,000 --> 01:28:43,920
(PEOPLE GRUMBLE AND COMPLAIN)

1269
01:28:44,080 --> 01:28:46,000
Get out, the whole lot of you!

1270
01:28:46,160 --> 01:28:49,760
- Where are we supposed to go?
- Yeah, where are we supposed to go?

1271
01:28:59,840 --> 01:29:01,520
PA SYSTEM: <i>This is a final warning.</i>

1272
01:29:01,680 --> 01:29:03,800
<i>Residents and non-residents
must register...</i>

1273
01:29:03,960 --> 01:29:05,840
- Ruth?
<i>- ...at the town hall for ID cards...</i>

1274
01:29:06,000 --> 01:29:08,000
It is Ruth, isn't it?

1275
01:29:09,600 --> 01:29:12,120
I'm Bob, Jimmy's mate.

1276
01:29:14,680 --> 01:29:16,680
We met once or twice, remember?

1277
01:29:18,760 --> 01:29:21,040
You came to our last Christmas do at work.

1278
01:29:25,120 --> 01:29:27,000
PA SYSTEM: <i>This is a final warning.</i>

1279
01:29:27,160 --> 01:29:29,160
Where is he?

1280
01:29:29,880 --> 01:29:31,720
Is he wi' you?

1281
01:29:31,880 --> 01:29:33,800
Have you seen him?

1282
01:29:33,960 --> 01:29:36,880
PA SYSTEM: <i>No provisions will be issued
to anyone without them.</i>

1283
01:29:37,040 --> 01:29:39,160
<i>Feeding will be now on alternate days.</i>

1284
01:29:40,040 --> 01:29:44,000
<i>Numbers 1-500 will be fed today,
the remainder tomorrow.</i>

1285
01:30:00,680 --> 01:30:02,600
RUTH: Is it safe to eat?

1286
01:30:02,760 --> 01:30:04,760
I don't know. How can you tell?

1287
01:30:08,400 --> 01:30:11,160
It's got a thick coat.
That should have protected it.

1288
01:30:11,320 --> 01:30:13,320
You breathe it in, though, don't you?

1289
01:30:13,480 --> 01:30:15,480
It should be all right.

1290
01:30:17,480 --> 01:30:19,400
Sheep don't die of cold.

1291
01:30:19,560 --> 01:30:21,560
It must be radiation.

1292
01:30:22,560 --> 01:30:25,280
You'd be able to taste it
if it were contaminated.

1293
01:30:25,440 --> 01:30:27,360
Oh, I don't know.

1294
01:30:27,520 --> 01:30:31,320
Anyway, we've no choice, have we,
unless we want to starve to death?

1295
01:30:34,080 --> 01:30:35,520
Oh!

1296
01:30:49,400 --> 01:30:51,320
I'll take some wi' me.

1297
01:30:51,480 --> 01:30:53,160
Where?

1298
01:30:55,320 --> 01:30:57,320
T'city.

1299
01:30:59,880 --> 01:31:01,880
There's nothing there.

1300
01:31:08,040 --> 01:31:09,600
North.

1301
01:31:09,760 --> 01:31:11,760
T'Dales.

1302
01:31:15,080 --> 01:31:17,080
It doesn't really matter, does it?

1303
01:31:19,640 --> 01:31:21,640
It's all the same.

1304
01:31:24,280 --> 01:31:26,200
(WIND GUSTING)

1305
01:31:26,360 --> 01:31:28,360
I'll try and skin it.

1306
01:31:30,000 --> 01:31:32,000
It'll keep me warm.

1307
01:31:54,240 --> 01:31:56,240
(WIND GUSTING)

1308
01:32:36,440 --> 01:32:39,520
RADIO: <i>If we are to survive
these difficult early months</i>

1309
01:32:39,680 --> 01:32:42,840
<i>and establish a firm base
for the redevelopment of our country,</i>

1310
01:32:43,000 --> 01:32:46,920
<i>then we must concentrate all our energies
on agricultural production.</i>

1311
01:33:00,160 --> 01:33:03,160
NARRATOR:
<i>Collecting this diminished first harvest</i>

1312
01:33:03,320 --> 01:33:05,720
<i>is now literally a
matter of life and death.</i>

1313
01:33:44,160 --> 01:33:46,080
(SHE GASPS)

1314
01:33:46,240 --> 01:33:48,240
(LABOURED BREATHING)

1315
01:33:58,760 --> 01:34:02,000
<i>Chronic fuel shortages mean
that this could be one of the last times</i>

1316
01:34:02,160 --> 01:34:05,240
<i>tractors and combine harvesters
are used in Britain.</i>

1317
01:34:31,520 --> 01:34:33,520
(DOGS BARK IN DISTANCE)

1318
01:34:42,080 --> 01:34:44,080
(BARKS)

1319
01:34:46,360 --> 01:34:48,360
(GROWLS AND SNARLS)

1320
01:34:58,160 --> 01:34:59,560
(BARKING)

1321
01:35:10,120 --> 01:35:11,960
(SHE MOANS)

1322
01:35:13,000 --> 01:35:14,920
(CRIES OUT IN PAIN)

1323
01:35:18,720 --> 01:35:20,720
(DOG GROWLS)

1324
01:35:30,200 --> 01:35:32,200
(SHE MOANS IN PAIN)

1325
01:35:40,160 --> 01:35:41,920
(MOANING)

1326
01:35:44,440 --> 01:35:46,440
(MOANING CONTINUES, DOG BARKS)

1327
01:35:50,560 --> 01:35:52,560
(BABY CRIES)

1328
01:35:53,680 --> 01:35:55,680
(CRYING CONTINUES)

1329
01:36:19,080 --> 01:36:21,080
(CRYING INTENSIFIES)

1330
01:36:28,000 --> 01:36:29,720
(RUTH SOBS)

1331
01:36:52,560 --> 01:36:54,560
(BABY CRYING)

1332
01:37:08,720 --> 01:37:10,720
(FIRE CRACKLING)

1333
01:37:39,920 --> 01:37:41,920
(WIND HOWLING)

1334
01:37:43,560 --> 01:37:45,560
NARRATOR: <i>The first winter.</i>

1335
01:37:46,800 --> 01:37:50,040
<i>The stresses of hypothermia,
epidemic and radiation</i>

1336
01:37:50,200 --> 01:37:52,520
<i>fall heavily on the very young and the old.</i>

1337
01:37:53,240 --> 01:37:55,400
<i>Their protective layers
of flesh are thinner.</i>

1338
01:37:56,240 --> 01:38:00,360
<i>In the first few winters, many of the young
and old disappear from Britain.</i>

1339
01:38:13,480 --> 01:38:15,360
(HELICOPTER WHIRS OVERHEAD)

1340
01:38:15,520 --> 01:38:16,960
PA SYSTEM: <i>Halt!</i>

1341
01:38:17,120 --> 01:38:19,560
<i>If you do not halt, we will open fire!</i>

1342
01:38:20,960 --> 01:38:22,600
<i>Halt at once.</i>

1343
01:38:23,480 --> 01:38:24,880
(GUNSHOT)

1344
01:38:26,680 --> 01:38:28,600
(POUNDING)

1345
01:38:28,760 --> 01:38:30,760
(SHE GRUNTS)

1346
01:38:33,640 --> 01:38:35,360
No!

1347
01:38:36,360 --> 01:38:38,360
(POUNDING CONTINUES)

1348
01:38:46,840 --> 01:38:48,400
(SHE BLOWS)

1349
01:38:50,160 --> 01:38:51,720
Ohh!

1350
01:40:00,120 --> 01:40:02,120
(HOE THUDS IN SOIL)

1351
01:40:29,520 --> 01:40:31,120
(FLIES BUZZING)

1352
01:41:05,320 --> 01:41:06,800
(RUTH GROANS)

1353
01:41:42,240 --> 01:41:43,560
Ruth.

1354
01:41:46,880 --> 01:41:48,280
Ruth.

1355
01:41:48,440 --> 01:41:50,040
Wake.

1356
01:41:51,040 --> 01:41:52,160
Wake.

1357
01:41:53,480 --> 01:41:54,920
Wake...

1358
01:41:55,840 --> 01:41:57,280
...up.

1359
01:42:58,600 --> 01:43:00,600
(TV THEME TUNE PLAYS)

1360
01:43:03,720 --> 01:43:05,280
<i>Words...</i>

1361
01:43:07,840 --> 01:43:08,920
<i>...And...</i>

1362
01:43:11,600 --> 01:43:13,040
<i>...Pictures.</i>

1363
01:43:17,840 --> 01:43:19,840
<i>Words And Pictures.</i>

1364
01:43:21,640 --> 01:43:26,800
<i>Skeletons and skulls
of different creatures.</i>

1365
01:43:27,720 --> 01:43:29,880
<i>We borrowed them from the museum.</i>

1366
01:43:30,040 --> 01:43:31,920
(CRACKLING INTERFERENCE ON TAPE)

1367
01:43:32,080 --> 01:43:35,160
<i>Did you recognise
what some of those skeletons were?</i>

1368
01:43:36,880 --> 01:43:38,880
<i>There was the skeleton of...</i>

1369
01:43:40,600 --> 01:43:41,920
<i>...a cat.</i>

1370
01:43:44,440 --> 01:43:46,280
<i>A cat's skeleton.</i>

1371
01:43:48,000 --> 01:43:50,000
<i>The skeleton of...</i>

1372
01:43:51,000 --> 01:43:52,160
<i>...a chicken.</i>

1373
01:43:53,760 --> 01:43:55,760
<i>A chicken's skeleton.</i>

1374
01:43:59,360 --> 01:44:00,920
<i>The skeleton of...</i>

1375
01:44:01,080 --> 01:44:02,880
<i>a bird.</i>

1376
01:44:04,080 --> 01:44:06,080
<i>A bird's skeleton.</i>

1377
01:44:08,160 --> 01:44:10,160
(MUSIC PLAYS ON TV)

1378
01:44:17,200 --> 01:44:19,200
(WATER DRIPPING)

1379
01:45:18,880 --> 01:45:20,880
(WIND HOWLING)

1380
01:45:44,480 --> 01:45:46,120
Oi!

1381
01:45:47,120 --> 01:45:48,320
What 'em be?

1382
01:45:48,480 --> 01:45:50,400
- See them. Coney.
- Give us 'em.

1383
01:45:50,560 --> 01:45:52,880
- Give us 'em!
- Better, else us'll pry 'em.

1384
01:45:53,040 --> 01:45:54,960
Best stand off, else tha'll get it.

1385
01:45:55,120 --> 01:45:57,120
(PANTING)

1386
01:45:59,240 --> 01:46:00,920
Give us 'em.

1387
01:46:03,280 --> 01:46:05,200
Where you stopped at?

1388
01:46:05,360 --> 01:46:07,360
Come with us?

1389
01:46:08,560 --> 01:46:10,480
- Where?
- Come on. Us place.

1390
01:46:10,640 --> 01:46:12,440
Gaz and Spike.

1391
01:46:14,080 --> 01:46:15,560
Share them coney, then.

1392
01:46:15,720 --> 01:46:17,520
Come on. Come and share 'em coney!

1393
01:46:17,680 --> 01:46:20,120
- Gi' us them! Come on, gi' us them!
- Us place, come on!

1394
01:46:20,280 --> 01:46:21,600
Come on!

1395
01:46:30,320 --> 01:46:31,880
MAN: Come back here wi' that!

1396
01:46:33,080 --> 01:46:34,640
Hey, you!

1397
01:46:34,800 --> 01:46:36,720
- Come back!
- (PANTING)

1398
01:46:36,880 --> 01:46:38,880
(GUNSHOTS)

1399
01:46:41,440 --> 01:46:42,920
Come back!

1400
01:46:43,080 --> 01:46:44,600
(GUNSHOT)

1401
01:46:47,000 --> 01:46:49,000
(PANTING)

1402
01:46:56,040 --> 01:46:57,960
Come on, then.

1403
01:46:58,120 --> 01:47:00,040
Gi' us it!

1404
01:47:00,200 --> 01:47:02,120
Come on!

1405
01:47:02,280 --> 01:47:03,960
Gi' us it.

1406
01:47:05,880 --> 01:47:07,400
Gi' us it.

1407
